04960nam a22005535i 9780226817071DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226817071  a(DE-B1597)619065  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aNB237 7aART0000002bisacsh04a730.921 aGetsy, David J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQueer Behavior :bScott Burton and Performance Art /cDavid J. Getsy. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b11 color plates, 72 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION Scott Burton’s Queer Postminimalism -- tSTREET AND STAGE EARLY EXPERIMENTS -- t1 IMITATE ORDINARY LIFE Self- Works, Literalist Theater, and Being Otherwise in Public, 1969– 70 -- t2 LANGUAGES OF THE BODY Theatrical, Feminist, and Scientific Foundations, 1970– 71 -- tPERFORMANCE AND ITS USES -- t3 THE EMOTIONAL NATURE OF THE NUMBER OF INCHES BETWEEN THEM Behavior Tableaux, 1972– 80 -- t4 ACTING OUT Queer Reactions and Reveals, 1973– 76 -- t5 PRAGMATIC STRUCTURES Sculpture and the Performance of Furniture, 1972– 79 -- tCONCLUSION Homocentric and Demotic -- tAPPENDIX List of Performances and Other Artworks by Scott Burton, 1969– 80 -- tNOTES -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tGENERAL INDEX -- tINDEX OF WORKS BY SCOTT BURTON0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first book to chart Scott Burton’s performance art and sculpture of the 1970s. Scott Burton (1939­–89) created performance art and sculpture that drew on queer experience and the sexual cultures that flourished in New York City in the 1970s. David J. Getsy argues that Burton looked to nonverbal body language and queer behavior in public space—most importantly, street cruising—as a foundation for rethinking the audiences and possibilities of art. Throughout the decade, he made complex works about bodies and how they communicate. Extending his performances about cruising, sexual signaling, and power dynamics, Burton also created functional sculptures that covertly signaled queerness by hiding in plain sight as furniture waiting to be used. With research drawing from multiple archives and numerous interviews, Getsy charts Burton’s deep engagements with postminimalism, performance, feminism, behavioral psychology, design history, and queer culture. A restless and wide-ranging artist, Burton transformed his commitment to gay liberation into a unique practice of performance, sculpture, and public art that aspired to be anti-elitist, embracing of differences, and open to all. Filled with stories of Burton’s life in New York’s art communities, Queer Behavior makes a case for Burton as one of the most significant out queer artists to emerge in the wake of the Stonewall uprising and, in so doing, provides a rich account of the interwoven histories of queer art and performance art in the 1970s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aART / General.2bisacsh  aperformance art, queer art, behavior, sculpture, cruising, LGBT, gay, public art, New York, postminimalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Architecture and Design 2022z9783110992793oZDB-23-DAD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishz978311099281608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.co